01:30:35,640 --> 01:30:38,640
So if we have our vector A,

2224
01:30:38,640 --> 01:30:43,640
which we represent by a column vector,

2225
01:30:43,640 --> 01:30:46,640
and I'm only going to write two-dimensional column vectors,

2226
01:30:46,640 --> 01:30:49,640
but you'll immediately deduce what to do

2227
01:30:49,640 --> 01:30:50,640
if you have a few more in your mind.

2228
01:30:51,640 --> 01:30:53,640
So let's do a few more entries here.

2229
01:30:53,640 --> 01:30:55,640
We can multiply it by a matrix,

2230
01:30:55,640 --> 01:30:59,640
and a matrix is a square array of numbers,

2231
01:30:59,640 --> 01:31:06,640
M11, M12, M21, M22.

2232
01:31:06,640 --> 01:31:10,640
And in general, these numbers are all complex numbers.

2233
01:31:10,640 --> 01:31:13,640
In general, they're all complex numbers.

2234
01:31:13,640 --> 01:31:16,640
The A's and the M's in a complex vector space

2235
01:31:16,640 --> 01:31:19,640
can all be complex numbers.

2236
01:31:19,640 --> 01:31:21,640
And the rule for matrix multiplication,

2237
01:31:21,640 --> 01:31:24,640
which I showed us last time,

2238
01:31:24,640 --> 01:31:27,640
for multiplying a matrix by a vector,

2239
01:31:27,640 --> 01:31:30,640
is just,

2240
01:31:30,640 --> 01:31:31,640
if you want the top entry,

2241
01:31:31,640 --> 01:31:33,640
which you can think of as the top row,

2242
01:31:33,640 --> 01:31:36,640
you take the top row,

2243
01:31:36,640 --> 01:31:39,640
and you multiply it by the vector.

2244
01:31:39,640 --> 01:31:41,140
You take the inner product of

2245
01:31:41,140 --> 01:31:42,640
the top row with the vector,

2246
01:31:42,640 --> 01:31:48,640
which will be M11A1

2247
01:31:48,640 --> 01:31:50,640
plus M12A2,

2248
01:31:51,640 --> 01:31:53,640
and then down here,

2249
01:31:53,640 --> 01:31:59,640
M21A1 plus M22A2.

2250
01:31:59,640 --> 01:32:01,640
So it's another vector.

2251
01:32:01,640 --> 01:32:03,640
I had to draw it pretty wide

2252
01:32:03,640 --> 01:32:05,640
because I was adding some numbers here,

2253
01:32:05,640 --> 01:32:06,640
but it's just a vector.

2254
01:32:06,640 --> 01:32:08,640
It's a column vector with one column,

2255
01:32:08,640 --> 01:32:11,640
and it's constructed by taking this row

2256
01:32:11,640 --> 01:32:12,640
times the column,

2257
01:32:12,640 --> 01:32:14,640
and this row times the column,

2258
01:32:14,640 --> 01:32:16,640
and those are the two entries.

2259
01:32:21,640 --> 01:32:22,640
That's it.

2260
01:32:22,640 --> 01:32:24,640
That's all that matrices are.

2261
01:32:24,640 --> 01:32:26,640
Let me give you a couple of examples,

2262
01:32:26,640 --> 01:32:28,640
a couple of simple examples

2263
01:32:28,640 --> 01:32:31,640
from a very ordinary vector space.

2264
01:32:31,640 --> 01:32:33,640
A very ordinary vector space

2265
01:32:33,640 --> 01:32:36,640
is just the pointers or the arrows

2266
01:32:36,640 --> 01:32:38,640
that you can draw on the blackboard.

2267
01:32:38,640 --> 01:32:41,640
You can multiply a vector by,

2268
01:32:41,640 --> 01:32:43,640
in this case, a real number.

2269
01:32:43,640 --> 01:32:45,640
You can double it, you can triple it,

2270
01:32:45,640 --> 01:32:47,640
you can multiply it by minus one,

2271
01:32:47,640 --> 01:32:49,640
and you can add two vectors.

2272
01:32:49,640 --> 01:32:51,640
So vectors that you draw on the blackboard

2273
01:32:51,640 --> 01:32:53,640
are a vector space.

2274
01:32:53,640 --> 01:32:54,640
Let me give you, and they have,

2275
01:32:54,640 --> 01:32:55,640
what are their components?

2276
01:32:55,640 --> 01:32:57,640
Their components are the x component,

2277
01:32:57,640 --> 01:33:01,640
here's x, here's y,

2278
01:33:01,640 --> 01:33:03,640
and the vector has an x component

2279
01:33:03,640 --> 01:33:06,640
and a y component.

2280
01:33:06,640 --> 01:33:08,640
So we represent this vector

2281
01:33:08,640 --> 01:33:11,640
by its x component and its y component,

2282
01:33:11,640 --> 01:33:13,640
and we could write it in the form

2283
01:33:13,640 --> 01:33:15,640
x component of vector,

2284
01:33:15,640 --> 01:33:17,640
y component of the vector.

2285
01:33:17,640 --> 01:33:18,640
Of course, now I'm only doing

2286
01:33:18,640 --> 01:33:19,640
two dimensions,

2287
01:33:19,640 --> 01:33:20,640
so I'm going to do

2288
01:33:20,640 --> 01:33:22,640
a two-dimensional space.

2289
01:33:22,640 --> 01:33:24,640
These would be real numbers

2290
01:33:24,640 --> 01:33:25,640
on the blackboard.

2291
01:33:25,640 --> 01:33:27,640
They wouldn't be complex numbers,

2292
01:33:27,640 --> 01:33:30,640
and this would be a two-real-dimensional vector space.

2293
01:33:30,640 --> 01:33:32,640
Now, let's think about some operations.

2294
01:33:32,640 --> 01:33:34,640
The first interesting operation,

2295
01:33:34,640 --> 01:33:36,640
which is the most easy,

2296
01:33:36,640 --> 01:33:38,640
is to stretch the vector space.

2297
01:33:38,640 --> 01:33:42,640
For example, multiply every vector by two.

2298
01:33:42,640 --> 01:33:43,640
Okay?

2299
01:33:43,640 --> 01:33:45,640
Multiply every vector by two

2300
01:33:45,640 --> 01:33:48,640
will sort of magnify the whole space

2301
01:33:48,640 --> 01:33:49,640
by a factor of two.

2302
01:33:49,640 --> 01:33:51,640
Any vector will get stretched out

2303
01:33:51,640 --> 01:33:53,640
to twice its original length.

2304
01:33:53,640 --> 01:33:55,640
That's all that happens.

2305
01:33:55,640 --> 01:33:57,640
Here's the matrix

2306
01:33:57,640 --> 01:34:00,640
that represents that operation.

2307
01:34:00,640 --> 01:34:04,640
It's just the diagonal matrix 2, 2.

2308
01:34:04,640 --> 01:34:07,640
Diagonal means that its entries

2309
01:34:07,640 --> 01:34:10,640
are along the diagonal.

2310
01:34:10,640 --> 01:34:13,640
There are two diagonals in the matrix.

2311
01:34:13,640 --> 01:34:14,640
This is called the principal diagonal,

2312
01:34:14,640 --> 01:34:15,640
I think, if I remember.

2313
01:34:15,640 --> 01:34:16,640
The other one is called

2314
01:34:16,640 --> 01:34:17,640
the unprincipled diagonal.

2315
01:34:17,640 --> 01:34:18,640
I don't know what it's called.

2316
01:34:19,640 --> 01:34:20,640
I don't know.

2317
01:34:20,640 --> 01:34:21,640
What?

2318
01:34:21,640 --> 01:34:22,640
Degenerate.

2319
01:34:22,640 --> 01:34:27,640
The good diagonal and the bad diagonal.

2320
01:34:27,640 --> 01:34:30,640
This one is the bad diagonal.

2321
01:34:30,640 --> 01:34:31,640
All right.

2322
01:34:31,640 --> 01:34:33,640
Let's just calculate what we get.

2323
01:34:33,640 --> 01:34:34,640
All right.

2324
01:34:34,640 --> 01:34:35,640
In the upper entry,

2325
01:34:35,640 --> 01:34:38,640
we get 2 times vx plus 0.

2326
01:34:38,640 --> 01:34:41,640
So the upper entry just becomes 2vx.

2327
01:34:41,640 --> 01:34:42,640
The lower entry,

2328
01:34:42,640 --> 01:34:44,640
we get 2 times vy.

2329
01:34:44,640 --> 01:34:46,640
So, as advertised,

2330
01:34:46,640 --> 01:34:48,640
this is the operator,

2331
01:34:48,640 --> 01:34:50,640
which simply doubles the length of every vector.

2332
01:34:50,640 --> 01:34:51,640
All right.

2333
01:34:51,640 --> 01:34:52,640
Very easy.

2334
01:34:52,640 --> 01:34:54,640
Here's a more,

2335
01:34:54,640 --> 01:34:58,640
almost a similar thing.

2336
01:34:58,640 --> 01:35:00,640
But supposing I just wanted to

2337
01:35:00,640 --> 01:35:02,640
double the y component.

2338
01:35:02,640 --> 01:35:04,640
What would that do to the vector space?

2339
01:35:04,640 --> 01:35:06,640
It would take every vector

2340
01:35:06,640 --> 01:35:08,640
and stretch out its y component

2341
01:35:08,640 --> 01:35:09,640
by a factor of 2

2342
01:35:09,640 --> 01:35:11,640
without stretching out its x component.

2343
01:35:11,640 --> 01:35:14,640
So it would be a stretch in the y direction

2344
01:35:14,640 --> 01:35:16,640
by a factor of 2,

2345
01:35:16,640 --> 01:35:18,640
but no stretch in the y direction

2346
01:35:18,640 --> 01:35:20,640
but in the x direction.

2347
01:35:20,640 --> 01:35:22,640
How would we represent that?

2348
01:35:22,640 --> 01:35:23,640
Okay.

2349
01:35:23,640 --> 01:35:26,640
Again, a diagonal with a 1 here

2350
01:35:26,640 --> 01:35:28,640
in the x place, in the xx,

2351
01:35:28,640 --> 01:35:31,640
and the yy place, the factor 2.

2352
01:35:31,640 --> 01:35:33,640
Let's check it.

2353
01:35:33,640 --> 01:35:36,640
1 times vx gives us vx.

2354
01:35:36,640 --> 01:35:39,640
2 times vy gives us twice vy.

2355
01:35:39,640 --> 01:35:41,640
So that's a stretching of the vector space

2356
01:35:41,640 --> 01:35:44,640
in the y direction.

2357
01:35:44,640 --> 01:35:46,640
Likewise, we could put the 2 here,

2358
01:35:46,640 --> 01:35:47,640
and the 1 here.

2359
01:35:47,640 --> 01:35:49,640
And the 1 here,

2360
01:35:49,640 --> 01:35:51,640
that would be a stretching of the vector space

2361
01:35:51,640 --> 01:35:54,640
which stretches it out in this direction.

2362
01:35:54,640 --> 01:35:56,640
One or two more.

2363
01:35:56,640 --> 01:35:58,640
These are very easy examples.

2364
01:35:58,640 --> 01:36:02,640
So far, they've only involved diagonal matrices.

2365
01:36:02,640 --> 01:36:04,640
Let me give you another one.

2366
01:36:04,640 --> 01:36:08,640
The matrix which corresponds to

2367
01:36:08,640 --> 01:36:12,640
rotating every vector by 90 degrees.

2368
01:36:12,640 --> 01:36:14,640
Take any vector

2369
01:36:14,640 --> 01:36:16,640
and rotate it by 90 degrees.

2370
01:36:16,640 --> 01:36:18,640
In other words, this is the operation

2371
01:36:18,640 --> 01:36:21,640
which rotates the plane by 90 degrees.

2372
01:36:21,640 --> 01:36:22,640
I'll tell you what it is,

2373
01:36:22,640 --> 01:36:24,640
and then we'll check and

2374
01:36:24,640 --> 01:36:26,640
see if we can see why.

2375
01:36:26,640 --> 01:36:29,640
It's off-diagonal.

2376
01:36:29,640 --> 01:36:32,640
Or...

2377
01:36:35,640 --> 01:36:40,640
1 minus 1, excuse me.

2378
01:36:40,640 --> 01:36:42,640
Oh, let's do this one first.

2379
01:36:42,640 --> 01:36:44,640
Let's do what this is.

2380
01:36:44,640 --> 01:36:45,640
Before I do the rotation,

2381
01:36:45,640 --> 01:36:46,640
let's do this.

2382
01:36:46,640 --> 01:36:48,640
Let's see what this does.

2383
01:36:48,640 --> 01:36:51,640
This takes 0 times vx,

2384
01:36:51,640 --> 01:36:53,640
1 times vy.

2385
01:36:53,640 --> 01:36:58,640
It interchanges vy and vx.

2386
01:36:58,640 --> 01:37:00,640
It interchanges vy and vx.

2387
01:37:00,640 --> 01:37:05,640
Anybody see geometrically what that corresponds to?

2388
01:37:05,640 --> 01:37:06,640
A reflection.

2389
01:37:06,640 --> 01:37:08,640
It's a reflection of the vector space

2390
01:37:08,640 --> 01:37:10,640
about this diagonal.

2391
01:37:10,640 --> 01:37:12,640
Takes every vector

2392
01:37:12,640 --> 01:37:14,640
and reflects it about that diagonal.

2393
01:37:15,640 --> 01:37:19,640
Just flips it about that diagonal.

2394
01:37:19,640 --> 01:37:23,640
That's this matrix.

2395
01:37:23,640 --> 01:37:24,640
Here's another matrix

2396
01:37:24,640 --> 01:37:29,640
where you put a minus 1 down here.

2397
01:37:29,640 --> 01:37:30,640
What does this give?

2398
01:37:30,640 --> 01:37:35,640
This gives vy minus vx.

2399
01:37:35,640 --> 01:37:38,640
vy minus vx.

2400
01:37:38,640 --> 01:37:41,640
It interchanges the x and y,

2401
01:37:41,640 --> 01:37:43,140
but then throws in a

2402
01:37:43,140 --> 01:37:44,640
minus sign for one of them.

2403
01:37:45,640 --> 01:37:47,640
That is an operation.

2404
01:37:47,640 --> 01:37:49,640
I'm going to leave it to you to prove

2405
01:37:49,640 --> 01:37:51,640
because we don't have time,

2406
01:37:51,640 --> 01:37:53,640
but I'm going to tell you what this does.

2407
01:37:53,640 --> 01:37:57,640
It rotates the vector space by 90 degrees.

2408
01:37:57,640 --> 01:38:00,640
Oh, does it go the other way?

2409
01:38:00,640 --> 01:38:06,640
It's an easy way to see all this.

2410
01:38:06,640 --> 01:38:08,640
Well, you know it.

2411
01:38:08,640 --> 01:38:10,640
It's going to rotate the other direction.

2412
01:38:10,640 --> 01:38:11,640
It negated it, so...

2413
01:38:11,640 --> 01:38:12,640
Yeah.

2414
01:38:12,640 --> 01:38:13,640
You negated the...

2415
01:38:13,640 --> 01:38:14,640
Yeah.

2416
01:38:14,640 --> 01:38:16,640
The y component.

2417
01:38:16,640 --> 01:38:20,640
It rotates every vector by 90 degrees.

2418
01:38:20,640 --> 01:38:21,640
Just the y component.

2419
01:38:21,640 --> 01:38:22,640
What's that?

2420
01:38:22,640 --> 01:38:24,640
Rotating it around the x axis.

2421
01:38:24,640 --> 01:38:26,640
The y component.

2422
01:38:26,640 --> 01:38:29,640
The x component is going into minus...

2423
01:38:29,640 --> 01:38:30,640
Right.

2424
01:38:30,640 --> 01:38:31,640
So where's the x?

2425
01:38:31,640 --> 01:38:32,640
The vector pointing in the x direction

2426
01:38:32,640 --> 01:38:35,640
is going into minus the vector pointing in the y.

2427
01:38:35,640 --> 01:38:36,640
So which way is it?

2428
01:38:36,640 --> 01:38:37,640
So what's it doing?

2429
01:38:37,640 --> 01:38:38,640
It's rotating by 90 degrees.

2430
01:38:38,640 --> 01:38:39,640
No, but 180 degrees.

2431
01:38:39,640 --> 01:38:40,640
Clockwise.

2432
01:38:40,640 --> 01:38:41,640
Oh, clock...

2433
01:38:41,640 --> 01:38:42,640
Rotating clockwise.

2434
01:38:42,640 --> 01:38:43,640
Yeah.

2435
01:38:43,640 --> 01:38:44,640
That's what I drew here.

2436
01:38:44,640 --> 01:38:45,640
Yeah.

2437
01:38:45,640 --> 01:38:46,640
Yeah.

2438
01:38:46,640 --> 01:38:47,640
Yeah.

2439
01:38:47,640 --> 01:38:48,640
It rotates the vector by 90 degrees.

2440
01:38:48,640 --> 01:38:51,140
So you see, what matrices correspond

2441
01:38:51,140 --> 01:38:53,640
to is they correspond to a...

2442
01:38:53,640 --> 01:38:57,640
Transformations of the vector space.

2443
01:38:57,640 --> 01:39:03,640
Stretchings, rotations, more complicated kinds of things.

2444
01:39:03,640 --> 01:39:05,640
Another example would be a shear.

2445
01:39:05,640 --> 01:39:06,640
A shear...

2446
01:39:06,640 --> 01:39:09,140
This is interesting to try to work out

2447
01:39:09,140 --> 01:39:11,640
the matrix that corresponds to a shear motion.

2448
01:39:11,640 --> 01:39:12,640
Let me tell you what a shear motion is.

2449
01:39:12,640 --> 01:39:13,640
A shear motion ish.

2450
01:39:13,640 --> 01:39:14,640
What a shear motion ish.

2451
01:39:14,640 --> 01:39:19,640
A shear motion takes every...

2452
01:39:19,640 --> 01:39:22,640
Well, it...

2453
01:39:22,640 --> 01:39:23,640
Oh, boy.

2454
01:39:23,640 --> 01:39:25,640
Slides stuff this way.

2455
01:39:25,640 --> 01:39:26,640
Okay?

2456
01:39:26,640 --> 01:39:30,640
So it slides you to the right by

2457
01:39:30,640 --> 01:39:34,640
an amount proportional to how high you are.

2458
01:39:34,640 --> 01:39:37,640
It takes every point and shifts it to the

2459
01:39:37,640 --> 01:39:40,640
right by an amount proportional to how high you are.

2460
01:39:40,640 --> 01:39:41,640
Okay?

2461
01:39:41,640 --> 01:39:45,700
to how high you are. There's a

2462
01:39:45,700 --> 01:39:49,760
matrix that describes that motion. Deforms the plane,

2463
01:39:50,340 --> 01:39:52,410
tilts this axis over, is what it does. I'm

2464
01:39:52,410 --> 01:39:54,480
not going to write that one out. I'll see

2465
01:39:54,480 --> 01:39:57,090
if you can find it the next time I'll

2466
01:39:57,090 --> 01:39:59,700
tell you what the answer is for a shear motion.

2467
01:40:00,400 --> 01:40:03,660
But in general, matrices correspond to

2468
01:40:03,660 --> 01:40:06,920
transformations, special transformations. Not all transformations

2469
01:40:06,920 --> 01:40:10,060
are represented as matrices. These are

2470
01:40:10,060 --> 01:40:13,200
the linear transformations, to be specific. But

2471
01:40:13,200 --> 01:40:16,060
these are the ones we're going to be interested

2472
01:40:16,060 --> 01:40:18,920
in. And we're going to be interested in a

2473
01:40:18,920 --> 01:40:22,740
special class of them. Now this is very abstract,

2474
01:40:22,740 --> 01:40:26,560
and for the moment you will not see why. This

2475
01:40:26,560 --> 01:40:29,290
is just definition. But I've got to give

2476
01:40:29,290 --> 01:40:32,020
you some mathematics and then intersperse it with

2477
01:40:32,020 --> 01:40:34,460
some physics. I'm going to give you the mathematics

2478
01:40:34,460 --> 01:40:36,900
today, and next time I'm going to show you

2479
01:40:36,900 --> 01:40:41,099
what the point is. There's a notion of

2480
01:40:41,099 --> 01:40:45,299
a Hermitian matrix. The notion of a Hermitian matrix

2481
01:40:45,299 --> 01:40:53,639
corresponds to the notion of a real number.

2482
01:40:53,639 --> 01:41:01,980
It's a kind of concept of reality versus imaginary,

2483
01:41:01,980 --> 01:41:05,540
but it doesn't mean that the entries are all real.

2484
01:41:06,900 --> 01:41:11,519
What it means, is that if you take an

2485
01:41:11,519 --> 01:41:16,139
element of the matrix, Mij. That's some element of

2486
01:41:16,139 --> 01:41:17,789
the matrix. It could be some big matrix, I

2487
01:41:17,789 --> 01:41:19,440
don't know how big it is, and it's somewhere

2488
01:41:19,440 --> 01:41:27,430
over here. And then there's Mji. Mji is

2489
01:41:27,430 --> 01:41:35,420
the reflected matrix element. If this is M12,

2490
01:41:35,420 --> 01:41:36,879
it would be over here.

2491
01:41:36,900 --> 01:41:38,639
then M21 would be over here.

2492
01:41:39,519 --> 01:41:41,339
M35 might be over here.

2493
01:41:41,480 --> 01:41:43,080
M53 would be over here.

2494
01:41:43,920 --> 01:41:46,460
So interchanging rows and columns

2495
01:41:46,460 --> 01:41:48,509
is a kind of reflection of

2496
01:41:48,509 --> 01:41:50,559
the matrix about the diagonal here.

